title: Rutgers line at disadvantage against Michigan State
text:
Rutgers line at disadvantage against Michigan State Ryan Dunleavy , @rydunleavy 5:45 p.m. EDT October 5, 2015 Buy Photo Rutgers right tackle J.J. Denman (77) celebrates a touchdown scored by tight end Matt Flanagan (81). (Photo: Mark Sullivan/Staff photographer) Buy Photo 4 CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN 1 COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
PISCATAWAY There is inexperience against experience and then there is three first-year starters against three fifth-year seniors. 
Otherwise known as Rutgers’ offensive line against Michigan State’s defensive line. 
On paper, it’s a mismatch as big as Saturday's game itself, with No. 4 Michigan State opening as a 17-point favorite against Rutgers. 
“For a young O-line like ourselves, something we’re going to have to focus on this week is our technique,” said left tackle Keith Lumpkin, one of the unit's two mainstays. “ For the guys that don’t really have the experience, they are going to get a true test of how much they prepared and how much they are going to have to work to block big-time guys.” 
Michigan State built an identity as one of the top defenses in the nation annually under former coordinator Pat Narduzzi, who left in the offseason to become the head coach at Pittsburgh. What is the roadmap to a Rutgers football bowl berth? 
Without him, Michigan State has slipped to the middle of the pack in the Big Ten, ranking No. 9 or No. 10 in the conference in points allowed per game (20.8), yards allowed per game (376.8), rushing yards allowed per game (128.0) and passing yards allowed per game (248.8). 
But don’t be fooled. 
“Michigan State’s defense plays with great effort,” right guard Chris Muller said. “The biggest thing is they play with great effort and they play with a lot of heart. They have a lot of big guys and the coaching over there is extraordinary. They are very fundamentally sound.” 
While Lumpkin and Muller got a first-hand look at Michigan State last season, right tackle J.J. Denman, left guard Dorian Miller and center Derrick Nelson are first-timers. 
And the fivesome’s first collective look at an elite front seven didn’t go well, as Rutgers allowed five sacks and managed 1.3 yards per carry on 32 rushing attempts in a 28-3 loss to Penn State.
